<font color="#FF0000">DUTY &amp; LOVE FOR AMERASIAN KIDS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jun  8 18:11:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Joe &amp; Art,<br>
     The problem is not whether the Vietnamese will let the Amerasians go, but whether the US will accept all of them.  It took years before we took any sizeable numbers, and then demanded detailed records that were very often no avialable.  The French have a much better record than we in this area.     <br>
                                                            <br>
     I remember reading a remark by the head of the human genome project that the things we set such store by are such a small fraction of genetic traits and that much greater genetic differences existed within racial groups than the differences that caused racial labels.<br>
                                                                One other thing, I wasn't a saint in Vietnam.  Was the original cherry lieutenant when I arrived, but an old warrant officer and a sergeant helped see to it that the situation was, in their minds, remedied.  Knew of no pregnancies for which I was responsible, but also know that there is no way of knowing that somewhere, someplace, I could have left a child behind, and I didn't exactly do a lot of catting around compared to many.  I do believe there is a collective responsibility here.  And if someone, someday would present me with DNA eveidence of paternity; I would be prepared to love such a son or daughter just as much as I love the 3 from my marriage.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


